## Conversation
Part of the "analyze import/init slowness" task. This is the demonstrated fix for
the #1 hotspot found by profiling: jsonschema's eager format-checker imports.

## Actions
- Found via -X importtime: rfc3987_syntax.syntax_helpers = 0.45s self (~40% of
  the whole `import weave`). Traced the chain: jsonschema -> jsonschema._format
  -> (installed extras) -> rfc3987_syntax builds a Lark grammar.
- Confirmed plain `import jsonschema` loads fqdn/isoduration/uri_template/
  webcolors/rfc3986_validator/rfc3987_syntax via sys.modules diff.
- grep showed only two top-level importers on the path:
  weave/trace_server/interface/builtin_object_classes/{annotation_spec,actions}.py.
- Both use jsonschema ONLY inside @field_validator / value_is_valid, never at
  module scope, so deferring the import is safe.
- Moved `import jsonschema` into the 3 functions with a comment explaining why.

## Errors & Mistakes
None for the edit itself. (See the profiler commit's note for the zsh
word-splitting mishap while generating before/after artifacts.)

## Dead Ends
- Considered preventing jsonschema's _format auto-import instead, but that's
  jsonschema-internal and depends on which extras are installed; the weave-side
  lazy import is the clean, robust fix.

## Hints for Future Agents
- This deviates from the repo's "imports at top of file" rule. It is an
  intentional, commented performance exception: the dep is heavy at import and
  only needed at validation time. Keep the explanatory comment if you touch it.
- The win only fully materializes when the jsonschema format extras (esp.
  rfc3987-syntax + lark) are installed in the environment; it's still a strict
  improvement otherwise (an unused-at-import dep is no longer imported eagerly).

## Codebase Discoveries
- weave never uses jsonschema format checking (calls validate() with no
  format_checker), so none of the format-checker libs are needed at all on the
  import path.

